descript.abstract: The City of Berkeley's council districts created during 2002 redistricting.
descript.purpose: This feature class originated as the final work product of Brian Quin's multi-meeting interaction with the Councilmembers involved with that work in 2002, the redistricting that was required due to updated block population counts, together with the City Attorney (Manuela Albuquerque's) direction that populations among the revised Council districts could not vary by more than 1%.
descript.supplinf:
The council districts were Brian Quinn's first project in February 2002; they were fully coincident with best available street centerline at that time, Centerline 6. For workflow, Brian used best available street centerline (Centerline 6) for lines, and edited the positions of some 1310 label points by hand to create a set of "precision" Census blocks for the entire city based on that centerline. The Council districts were dissolved from those.
The feature class originated as the final work product of Brian's multi-meeting interaction with the Councilmembers involved with that work in 2002, the redistricting that was required due to updated block population counts, together with the City Attorney (Manuela Albuquerque's) direction that populations among the revised Council districts could not vary by more than 1%.
For any updates following the next Census, or if you choose to make use of Centerline 10.8 as line work in the future, any centroids that would be generated from the existing precision census blocks should remain safely within the revised blocks---that wasn't the case when Brian started from Census 2000 TIGER blocks.
For current internal CoB use, there might be very minor (< 2 meters) alignment differences between the precision blocks and the various Centerline 10 versions through 106. Centelrine 108 has the divided streets divided into two parallel lines, so some decision would need to be made about which side goes to which Council district---if you chose to use CL108.
